## 1.1 Research Background: Why Reject Traditional Gamification?

**The Three Pitfalls of Traditional Gamification**

Existing applications (Habitica, Duolingo) predominantly employ competitive mechanisms: leaderboards, points, badges, and streak systems. While effective short-term, these designs cause long-term harm:

1. Heightened Anxiety  
    Leaderboards generate feelings of failure among users who fall behind—particularly dangerous in mental health contexts (Deterding et al., 2011)\[1\]  
    [https://doi.org/10.1145/2181037.2181040](https://doi.org/10.1145/2181037.2181040)  
2. Motivation Misalignment  
   Users participate to "earn badges" rather than pursue genuine growth; extrinsic rewards crowd out intrinsic motivation (Ryan & Deci, 2000)\[2\]  
    [https://doi.org/10.1037/0003-066X.55.1.68](https://doi.org/10.1037/0003-066X.55.1.68)  
3. Social Pressure  
    Public performance comparisons create shame, especially in reflection and emotion-tracking scenarios (Sardi et al., 2017)\[3\]  
    [https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbi.2017.05.011](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbi.2017.05.011)

**Our Design Philosophy: Anti-Gamification**

| Reject  | Adopt  |
| :---: | :---: |
| Points & Experience | Collaborative Milestones  |
| Leaderboards & Levels | Privacy-Preserving Progress Visibility  |
| Competitive Badges | Lightweight Mutual Support (Emoji)  |
| Punishment Mechanisms | Positive Reinforcement \+ Intrinsic Motivation  |

## **1.2 Competitive Analysis**

### **1.2.1 Forest: The Double-Edged Sword of Shared Goals**

![][image1]

Core Mechanism: 2-20 users focus simultaneously to "plant trees"; if anyone exits the app, all trees wither.

**Strengths:**

* Shared accountability reinforces persistence  
* Forest growth visualizes collective achievement  
* Eliminates comparison anxiety through removal of individual rankings

**Weaknesses:**

* High-Pressure Collaboration: Individual mistakes affect entire team → 18% of users mention "teammate disappointment" (App Store analysis)  
* Single-Dimension Tracking: Only measures focus time; cannot reflect emotional/relational growth

**Design Implications for QuestLabs:**

* Retain: Shared milestone concept ("Group completes 20 reflections this week")  
* Improve: Individual mistakes don't impact team → Cumulative contribution system  
* Improve: Synchronous → Asynchronous → Complete at own time, real-time progress updates

### **1.2.2 Strava: Gold Standard for Privacy-Preserving Social Visibility**

![][image2]

Core Mechanism: "Fuzzy visibility" design—shows friends exercised without displaying competitive data (pace, heart rate) unless user voluntarily shares.

**Strengths:**

* Reduces Comparison Anxiety: See "others are active" not "how much better they perform"  
* Lightweight Interaction: Kudos (0.5 sec) vs Comments (15+ sec) → 5× participation rate  
* Proven Efficacy: Munson & Consolvo (2012) research confirms moderate social visibility increases persistence by 43% without increasing anxiety\[6\]

**Weaknesses:**

* Large-scale networks (hundreds of friends) → Information overload  
* Asynchronous interaction lacks depth

**Design Implications for QuestLabs:**

Visibility Hierarchy:

* Level 1 (All Visible): "Your Cohort has 4/5 people who completed reflection today"  
* Level 2 (Anonymous Notification): "Someone just completed a deep reflection"  
* Level 3 (Never Display): Specific mood scores, reflection content

Interaction Design:

* Default: Emoji quick reactions  
* Optional: Brief encouragement (≤10 words)  
* Reject: Mandatory comments

### **1.2.3 Habitica: Cautionary Tale of Over-Gamification**

![][image3]

Core Mechanism: RPG-ified to-do list—completing tasks earns XP/gold, team up to battle bosses, teammate mistakes damage entire party.

**Strengths:**

* Gamification drives high engagement (Hamari et al., 2014: 48% engagement boost)\[8\]  
* Strong team belonging (party chat, shared battles)

**Weaknesses:**

* Motivation Displacement: Nicholson (2015) critiques "meaningless gamification"—users engage for rewards not genuine growth\[9\]  
* Social Pressure Returns: Individual mistakes affect team → Blame culture

**Design Implications for QuestLabs:**

Explicitly Reject:

* RPG elements (XP, levels, equipment)  
* Battle/conflict narratives  
* Individual mistakes penalizing team

Alternative Approach:

* From: Defeat Boss → Earn Equipment  
* To: Reach Milestone → Celebrate Growth  
* Retain team task concept, strip game mechanics

## **1.3 Five Core Design Principles**

### **Principle 1: Privacy-Preserving Visibility**

Design Principle: Display "activity occurrence" not "performance quality"

| Context | Traditional Design  | QuestLabs Design |
| :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Fitness Tracking | "John ran 10km, 4:30 pace" | "Friend completed a run"  |
| Mood Tracking | "John's mood: 3/5 (low)"  | "Your Cohort: 4/5 completed reflection" |
| Goal Progress  | Individual completion % ranking | Group cumulative progress bar |

Literature Support: Cialdini & Goldstein (2004): "Aggregated feedback preserves motivational benefits of social comparison while eliminating anxiety from direct performance comparison"\[12\]

---

### **Principle 2: Collective Goals Over Individual Competition**

Best Practice: Cumulative group goals \+ Asynchronous completion \+ No punishment \= High motivation \+ Low pressure

QuestLabs Application:

Group Goal: "Complete 20 reflections this week"

Mechanism:

* Each person contributes their part (asynchronous)  
* Real-time progress bar updates  
* Achieved → Celebration animation  
* Not achieved → No punishment, fresh start next week

Visual: \[Progress Bar\] 18/20 \- "Just 2 more to reach this week's milestone\!"

---

### **Principle 3: Low-Friction Interactions**

Key Insight: Slack data shows emoji reactions comprise 67% of all interactions, text replies only 33%

QuestLabs Application:

Encouragement Board:

* Anonymous Update: "Someone just completed their 5th reflection this week"  
* Quick Reactions: One-click emoji (0.5 seconds)  
* Optional Message: Brief text (\<10 words, optional)

Design Hierarchy:

* Default → Emoji (Lower barrier)  
* Optional → Brief message (Provide depth)  
* Reject → Mandatory detailed feedback (Avoid pressure)

---

### **Principle 4: Asynchronous Collaboration**

QuestLabs Application:

Fully Asynchronous Design:

1. Daily Check-in: Each person selects their time (7am-11pm) → Completion updates progress bar → Others see progress change  
2. Weekly Planning: Complete anytime Sunday-Monday → View "Teammate set 3 goals"  
3. Reflection Journal: Write anytime → Optional sharing → Asynchronous reactions

Advantages: Accommodates different schedules, timezone-friendly, reduces social pressure, maintains sense of connection

---

### **Principle 5: Journey Narrative Over Game Mechanics**

QuestLabs Application:

Language Design:

* "You've maintained reflection for 7 days—meaningful progress"  
* "This week you took a step forward in emotional awareness"  
* "Your Cohort is growing together"

Core Difference: Gamification focuses on external markers (badges, levels); Journey-fication focuses on internal change (**awareness, growth**)

Literature Support: Nicholson (2015) "Meaningful Gamification" theory: "Truly effective design helps users find personal meaning in activities. Journey narratives achieve this better because focus is on 'who I am' and 'who I'm becoming,' not 'what I got'"\[9\]
